date-released: 2026-06-02
version: "1.1"
abstract: >
  DCS (Durable Context Spine) is an architectural pattern for the temporal-
  persistence layer of agent systems, the substrate that lets project state,
  memory, and knowledge survive the context-window boundary, disconnected
  sessions, and the passage of time. Where ACS coordinates agents within a run
  (the concurrency axis), DCS persists what survives across runs (the temporal
  axis). It addresses four documented failure modes of long-lived agent work:
  false completion (declaring done on unverified work), inherited mess (no clean
  handoff state), the re-derivation tax (re-discovering orientation every
  session), and durable-state rot (stale memory that misleads). The pattern is
  defined as ten principles plus reference SLAs and a numbered build sequence. It
  is the companion spec to PDS (which scopes one agent's tools) and ACS (which
  coordinates many agents within a run); DCS persists the state they share.
